# Architecture Clusters LLM Guide

## Purpose

Use this command to inspect dependency pressure by grouped source areas. It helps identify dense or influential areas before planning edits.

## When To Run

- Before broad refactors.
- When choosing the safest starting point for untangling dependencies.
- When a change may affect many related files.

## How To Read The Result

- Higher pressure suggests more imports, dependents, edges, or lines.
- Incoming edges show who relies on a cluster.
- Outgoing edges show what a cluster relies on.
- Key files are useful entry points for exploration, not automatic ownership boundaries.

## Examples

- If a cluster has many incoming edges, treat edits there as high blast-radius work.
- If a cluster has many outgoing edges, inspect whether it is doing too much coordination.
- If a small cluster has high pressure, consider whether it is a hidden shared dependency.
- If a cluster has no dependents, it may be safer for exploratory refactoring.

## Agent Tips

- Use this for orientation, not pass/fail validation.
- Prefer changing lower-pressure areas first when the goal is incremental work.
- Combine this with the boundaries command before finalizing architecture changes.
- Do not infer policy from clusters alone; policy comes from the configured agreement.
